> Josh,
>
> If you are interested in corporate values and culture, I'm wondering if
> you'd be interested in reading a document I'd created for my business whi=
ch
> I built and ran for 18 years.
>
> The document was simply called an F. A. Q. and it was a very detailed
> description of our mission, our stakeholders and our values, and just as
> importantly, what we didn't value and who wasn't a stakeholder. it
> described the things our business was predicated on and included the
> criterion by which we could know when it was time to shut down. It inform=
ed
> everything we did. It was a statement of philosophy as much as anything
> else.
>
> About 9 years in another firm expressed an interest in buying a majority
> stake in my business. They asked me to bring a business plan, create a
> pitch book and give a half hour presentation to their chief investment
> officer.
>
> I did none of that.
>
> Instead I bought our F. A. Q. and began going through it.
>
> The CIO turned beet red. He said, "What's this shit? I want to see
> pro-formas, I want to see technology, I want to see plans. I need R. O. I=
."
>
> I said, "If we don't agree on first principles then the only thing you
> will ever be is a competitor, and there is no way I'm sharing any of that
> with you. Your time is valuable, but so is mine. You said you'd give me 3=
0
> minutes and I'm taking it. Now, shut up and pay attention."
>
> I walked him through the document. About 15 minutes in his demeanor
> softened and as I approached the end he began laughing.
>
> He said, "I've been doing this for 22 years and in no instance did a
> business plan survive the first year. And, in every instance where a
> business fell apart it was because they and we didn't see eye-to-eye on o=
ne
> of the things you've addressed. I like what you've done and I want to
> invest in your business."
>
> I said, "What business? I haven't even told you what we do yet."
>
> He said, "I don't care. Any business you can run on these terms I want to
> be a part of."
>
> I told him that the biggest risk to our business was not to the market or
> to our ideas but to the *character *of our investors. For that reason,
> the next step was that I needed to interview him, his staff and his major
> investors so that I might judge *their *character and determine what
> principles *they *live by.
>
> He agreed to that and I spent a half day with them. I even composed a
> written test and collected impromptu essays from them. Even if they had n=
ot
> heretofore lived according to the words they gave me I made it clear I
> would hold them to their rhetoric henceforth.
>
> They did pretty well, so I gave them a final test. I had a competing offe=
r
> from another firm that was not structured as an equity stake but an
> investment management and IP deal where I retained 100% ownership.
>
> Because if the investor bought into my company then we'd be partners
> working for the benefit of both of us, I told them to evaluate both the
> competing deal and their own and give me a recommendation and I'd do what
> they suggest. But, they had to understand that if they recommended I go
> with them and later I found out they did it because it was in their best
> interest but not mine then they would have one hell of a pissed-off partn=
er.
>
> They did as I asked and spent a day with the competition getting the
> details of their deal and auditing their character.
>
> Then they gave me a report recommending I go with the competition and not
> them.
>
> This is the power of well-articulated and well-lived mission and values.
> Often when  an investor comes along people start seeing an exit strategy
> and dollar signs and start jumping through absurd hoops that can often
> destroy their focus and even their business.
>
> I didn't have to do that. I had a long-standing document that guided our
> behavior and that gave me the courage to dictate terms and interact with
> others as I did.
>
> After auditing the investor's character I didn't have to do anything. The=
y
> are the ones, for example, who created a business plan for a business as
> they could imagine it after we were partners and they submitted it to me
> for my approval. And they are the ones who compared that to the competiti=
on
> and they determined their offer was inferior.
>
> We really didn't have to do anything except be who we are and hold them t=
o
> who they said they were.
>
> That is what character is; it is who we are. The first step is to say who
> that is so you can know who to be when things get confusing. There were
> plenty of well-run endeavors before the mobile device, the personal
> computer and even before the discovery of electricity.
>
> There is power in the written word, and IMHO the word and the will are
> both necessary and sufficient. That document was everything and I don't
> think our performance could have been improved by an app.
>
> If you'd like to discuss values and culture then I'd like to send you tha=
t
> document if you think you'll have time to read it by next week.
>
> Brooke
>
> P. S. That investor wanted to buy into us in 2005. Every deal they did
> with others fell apart by 2009 whereas we went strong through the entire
> financial collapse and didn't shut down until 2014 only a few basis point=
s
> off an all-time high. We shut down because the conditions on which our
> business was predicated had faded and there was no longer a point. Shutti=
ng
> down isn't what most people do at the top of the business cycle S-curve.
> Instead they either drive themselves off a cliff or try to sell to a
> greater fool. We could have done that but it would have violated our stat=
ed
> principles.
